name: Aga Khan Centre
description: The Aga Khan Centre, designed by Pritzker prize winning architect Fumihiko Maki, houses the UK institutions of the Aga Khan Development Network. A unique feature are its six gardens inspired by different regions of the Muslim world.
address: Aga Khan Centre, 10 Handyside Street, N1C 4DN

name: Alderman Jones House
description: Becontree Estate two storey cottage house with garden located on a banjo.

name: Barking Town Centre Tour
description: Barking town centre has seen significant development over recent years with substantial growth in housing and infrastructure. These guided tours will visit existing award winning schemes and set out the vision for the future of the town.

name: Belle Vue
description: Belle Vue is a holistic retirement community, set within landscaped courts and gardens with communal and neighbourhood facilities.

name: Boston Manor House and Park Walks
description:
Visitors will be shown around Boston Manor Park on short walks led by volunteers, focusing on the History of Boston Manor House and area.
The House is closed as part of a 5 year redevelopment project, re-opening early 2022.
address: Boston Manor House, Boston Manor Road, Brentford, TW8 9JX

name: Celebrating workplaces of key workers: The Story of Schools - a virtual tour with a London Blue Badge Tourist Guide
description: School and former school buildings dot the urban landscape - from Bluecoat Schools, Ragged Schools and huge numbers of Board Schools they tell the history of education in London.

name: Creating thoughtful homes with Studio Hallett Ike
description: Studio Hallett Ike take We Design Homes through a journey of award-winning home the ‘ER Residence’, as well as other upcoming exceptionally designed homes driven by a want to deliver meaningful, articulate and passionate architecture.

name: Cycle the City with PTE
description: Join architects, Pollard Thomas Edwards on an afternoon of ‘post occupancy evaluation by bike’, a fun way to analyse the impact of some of their completed projects in central London.
address: Motion, Lea Bridge Road , Waltham Forest , E10 7NU

name: Dreamings collage art exhibition
description: A collage art exhibition. Every day except Monday and Tuesday. A talk "Why Collage?" on Sunday evening at 7, followed by a Q&A and an art raffle for charity
address: The Brook Pub, 38 New Rd, Brentford TW8 0NU, TW8 0NU

name: Enfield To Fork - Edmonton Green Shopping Centre
description: The Museum of Enfield is this year bringing its temporary exhibition to you! “From Enfield to Fork” explores the borough’s history and relationship with food, from Roman Enfield to Market Gardening.

name: Enterprise Centre
description: A pioneering thatched building for the University of East Anglia, designed according to whole-life carbon principles and with the innovative use of natural and bio-based materials . Shortlisted for the Open City Stewardship Awards 2021.
address: University of East Anglia Research Park, University Drive, Norwich, NR4 7TJ

name: Estorick Collection of Modern Italian Art
description: The Estorick Collection is housed in a beautiful Georgian building previously known as Northampton Lodge. Today, the museum comprises six galleries over three floors, as well as a library, offices, a café and bookshop.

name: Flow Gallery
description: The interior of the building was redesigned in 2014 by John Pardey  to combine a craft gallery with a live work space for the gallery owner. Inspired by Kettle's Yard Flow space exhibits ceramics, glass, wood, textiles and jewellery.

name: German Historical Institute
description: This Grade II* listed building includes an Adam-style ceiling on the 1st floor and a beautiful staircase with wrought-iron balustrade. Once home to the Pharmaceutical Society of Great Britain, it now houses an historical research institute.

name: Guildhall Art Gallery
description: Houses the City of London's art collection, built over remains of London's 2C Roman amphitheatre. Façade uses Portland stone and Collyweston stone slates. Interior uses finishes of marble, American elm, damask and painted wall coverings.

name: Hyde Park Chapel
description: The four-story Church façade and prominent seven-story tower is covered in Portland stone and highlighted by a golden steeple. The interior features the Christus statue and a large mural of the resurrected Jesus Christ.

name: Isokon Building (Lawn Road Flats)
description: Grade I listed 1934 residential block of flats in Hampstead, designed by the Canadian modernist architect Wells Coates for clients Jack and Molly Pritchard. English Heritage blue plaque for Bauhaus masters Gropius, Breuer and Moholy-Nagy.

name: London Borough of Richmond upon Thames - a virtual tour with a London Blue Badge Tourist Guide
description:
A virtual Thames river cruise from Hampton Court Palace to Kew Gardens seeing 3 palaces, 2 stately homes plus the residences of the rich and famous, all set in beautiful scenery.
Led by Anna Targett who focuses on period, palaces and pomp.
address: The Green, Richmond upon Thames, TW10 2FG

name: Maggie's Barts
description: Maggie's Barts opened in December 2017. Maggie's Centres are unique, welcoming and uplifting places with qualified staff on hand to provide free practical, emotional and social support for people with cancer, their families and friends.

name: Marx Memorial Library & Workers' School
description: Grade II listed, built as a Welsh Charity School in 1738. A library with a focus on Marxism and Socialism since 1933. Lenin worked here 1902-03 and his office is preserved. Fresco by Jack Hastings in 1st floor. Late 15C tunnels.

name: Museum of Neoliberalism
description: The museum is situated in a shopfront in Leegate Shopping Centre, which has been described by the Evening Standard as "the worst shopping precinct in the country."

name: National Youth Theatre
description: Completed in Summer 2021, the National Youth Theatre has been redeveloped to double its capacity for studio space and was designed with young people, for young people. Recipient of the Mayor of London's Good Growth Fund.

name: Putting the Park in Wembley Park: an exclusive preview of Wembley Park's emerging Union Park and botanical tour of the neighbourhood's green spaces.
description: Quintain, the award-winning team behind the £3bn regeneration of Wembley Park, will host a series of guided tours of Wembley Park's emerging 7-acre Union Park and other new green spaces across the neighbourhood.
address: Olympic Steps, Olympic Way, Wembley Park, HA9 0NP

name: Reliance Arcade
description: Reliance Arcade is a Grade II Listed covered market in Brixton, London.  The Arcade was constructed in the 1920s and is home to 40 small retail units catering largely to local African-Caribbean communities.

name: Ripple Greenway and the Lost Words Art Trail
description:
Ripple Greenway is a beautiful 14-acre linear park and art trail.  Home to Katy Hallett’s steel sculptures, inspired by Robert Macfarlane’s and Jackie Morris’ The Lost Words.
Wooden play and exercise equipment, picnic tables and benches.

name: Self-guided Old Malden Walk
description: The walk is around Old Malden and covers residential developments within the district. Different styles of suburban architecture includes a selection of modernist housing. There are also historic buildings and other places of interest.
address: Manor Drive North, Greater London, KT3 5PN

name: Sociable housing in a time of social distancing
description: How can housing designed for nature and community impact on health and wellbeing, and create more crisis-resilient neighbourhoods?

name: St Bride's Church, Fleet Street
description: Wren designed building of 1675, interior lost in blitz of 1940, reopened 1957 with 'Wren inspired' interior
address: St Bride's Church, St Bride's Avenue, EC4Y 8AU

name: St Dunstan and All Saints Church
description: Grade I listed early medieval parish church (from 952 before Tower of London) in spacious churchyard. Fine interior: Anglo-Saxon Rood, Norman font, 'squint', fine memorials incl founders of Trinity House, 1950s glass. Bells of Stepney.

name: St James the Less Church
description: One of London's best Victorian churches and a key building in the history of the Gothic Revival. Polychromatic brickwork, with internal art work by G.F. Watts and Thomas Earp, windows and painted ceiling by Clayton and Bell. Grade I listed.
address: Thorndike Street, , off Moreton Street, SW1V 2PS

name: St Margaret's Church, Lee
description:
The Church was built in 1839/41 as a white 'Hall-Church'. 
The 1870s Gothic Revivalism was overseen to a very high standard, by James Brooks and helped by 10 top craftsmen of the day. We also have a WWI Memorial by Violet Pinwill.
address: St Margarets Church,  Lee Terrace, SE13 5DN

name: St. Ann's Hospital
description: st ann's
address: Mayfield House, St Ann's Road, Tottenham, N15 3TH

name: Studio Flox
description: Studio Flox at Watermans Art Centre is a combined arts centre. It is located in Brentford, England alongside the banks of the River Thames overlooking Kew Gardens in West London, England
address: WATERMANS PARK, 40A, HIGH STREET, BRENTFORD, TW8 0BB

name: The Church of Our Most Holy Redeemer
description: A unique II* listed Italianate church by John Dando Sedding with attached Campanile and Institute Building. Of particular significance in the church is the imposing baldacchino over the High Altar, which dominates the east end.

name: The City Centre
description: An overview of the latest developments and architecture in the City of London via the interactive 1:500 scale Pipers model that shows the future skyline with all of the proposed new towers.
address: City Centre, within Guildhall Complex (entrance at 80 Basinghall Street, leading from Gresham Street), EC2V 5AR

name: The Ismaili Centre
description: Part of an international family of Ismaili Centres, a religious, cultural and social space for the Shia Ismaili Muslim community. The serenity of the entrance fountain to the roof garden reflects Muslim traditions in architecture and design

name: The Library at Willesden Green
description: A modern 4-storey building incorporating the much-loved Victorian library. The galleries and feature walls display exhibitions and contemporary art and a dramatic central atrium provides natural ventilation and daylight throughout.

name: The Old Finsbury Town Hall
description: Opened by Lord Rosebery, an ornate building with elegant decor influenced by the Art Nouveau movement. Several notable rooms including the Great Hall with unique stained glass, antique mirrors and Clerkenwell Angel statuettes.

name: Trafalgar Tavern
description: A grand riverside Victorian pub, named after Horatio Nelson's victory at the Battle of Trafalgar. Featuring hundreds of original paintings on the walls.

name: Wellbeing Walk: Covent Garden
description: Our walking tour takes inspiration from the streets of Covent Garden to explore practical ways to support mental wellbeing and find pools of calm in the midst of London’s buzz and bustle.

name: ‘A tonic to the nation’: South Bank 1951-2021
description: Focussing on how the South Bank’s unique location and pattern of land ownership has shaped its history, the tour will address how businesses, communities, and locals have played a part in the area’s growth, management, and conservation
address: The Queen's Walk, South Bank , SE1 8XX
